1
00:01:30,523 --> 00:01:34,015
[Woman]
And so, the pages turn,

2
00:01:34,094 --> 00:01:36,654
and your school days are over.

3
00:01:36,729 --> 00:01:41,928
To you, they have been
a small, and we hope,
happy lifetime.

4
00:01:42,001 --> 00:01:46,028
But to us, they've been more
like the miracle of a minute.

5
00:01:46,106 --> 00:01:50,133
The mischievous, loving children
who came to us four years ago...

6
00:01:50,210 --> 00:01:53,805
now leave us
as charming young ladies,

7
00:01:53,880 --> 00:01:56,872
to face the challenge of life,

8
00:01:56,950 --> 00:02:00,044
with all the happiness
and victories...

9
00:02:00,120 --> 00:02:03,817
and even the disappointments
it has in store for you.

10
00:02:03,890 --> 00:02:08,520
No senior class
has ever set a higher standard
for succeeding ones to follow,

11
00:02:08,595 --> 00:02:10,563
and I only hope that now,

12
00:02:10,630 --> 00:02:13,793
when you go home
to friends and family,

13
00:02:13,867 --> 00:02:18,861
you will carry with you
all the courage and idealism...

14
00:02:18,938 --> 00:02:22,203
and the sportsmanship
that have made us all...

15
00:02:22,275 --> 00:02:25,676
so proud to be associated
with this graduating class.

16
00:02:27,514 --> 00:02:30,176
Good-bye, girls.

17
00:02:30,250 --> 00:02:33,913
Good luck.
God bless you.

18
00:02:37,357 --> 00:02:50,862
[Skipped item nr. 18]

19
00:02:50,937 --> 00:03:04,647
[Skipped item nr. 19]

20
00:03:04,717 --> 00:03:07,379
[Girls Shrieking,
Chattering]

21
00:03:12,992 --> 00:03:14,721
I can't find mine either.

22
00:03:14,794 --> 00:03:18,457
You'd think they'd have
sense enough to stay put.
There they are!
Connie!

23
00:03:18,531 --> 00:03:20,624
You've got to meet
Mother and Dad.

24
00:03:22,168 --> 00:03:24,102
Mother, Dad,
this is Connie.

25
00:03:24,170 --> 00:03:27,105
We're so glad
to meet you, after all
Marcia has written.

26
00:03:27,173 --> 00:03:29,107
She gave you
quite a buildup.
Oh.

27
00:03:29,175 --> 00:03:32,167
Well, look at her.
She's tops. And you
ought to hear her sing.

28
00:03:32,245 --> 00:03:35,908
When she hits
a high note, it sends chills
up and down your back.

29
00:03:35,982 --> 00:03:39,076
Where are your father
and mother, Connie?
We'd like to meet them.

30
00:03:39,152 --> 00:03:42,383
My parents are dead,
Mr. Parker.
Oh. I'm sorry.

31
00:03:42,455 --> 00:03:45,982
Mother, I have a wonderful idea.
Why can't Connie come with us
and spend the summer?

32
00:03:46,059 --> 00:03:48,391
Could you, Connie?
We'd be so pleased.

33
00:03:48,461 --> 00:03:52,363
It's very kind of you,
but I have an aunt
and uncle in New York.

34
00:03:52,432 --> 00:03:55,890
I'm going to live with them.
It's all been arranged that way.

35
00:03:55,969 --> 00:03:58,529
Her uncle is
James F. Clinton.
You know him, Dad.

36
00:03:58,605 --> 00:04:02,598
I owe everything
to UncleJim... this school,
my music, everything.

37
00:04:02,675 --> 00:04:05,405
- I couldn't disappoint him.
- No, of course not.

38
00:04:05,478 --> 00:04:09,073
Jim Clinton, eh?
Well, you're a lucky girl.
He's a fine man.

39
00:04:09,148 --> 00:04:12,276
- Yes, he is.
- Isn't it his daughter
we read so much about?

40
00:04:12,352 --> 00:04:15,947
Yes, that's Barbara.
She's a year older than I am.
Oh, and she's beautiful.

41
00:04:16,022 --> 00:04:18,547
Did you see her picture
in the magazine?

42
00:04:18,625 --> 00:04:21,025
Miss Constance Harding?
Yes.

43
00:04:21,094 --> 00:04:24,427
I'm Mr. Clinton's butler.
We've called for you in the car.

44
00:04:24,497 --> 00:04:27,728
Then they're here!
Excuse me, please.
Oh, no!

45
00:04:27,800 --> 00:04:31,429
They're not here.
I'm sorry, but only the
chauffeur and I are here.

46
00:04:33,139 --> 00:04:35,505
They didn't come?
No, miss, they
were very busy.

47
00:04:37,076 --> 00:04:40,102
Of course.
They couldn't leave
New York, could they?

48
00:04:40,179 --> 00:04:43,046
No, miss.
[Quietly]
Well.

49
00:04:43,116 --> 00:04:45,676
I'll be back
in a few minutes.
Very good, miss.

50
00:04:45,752 --> 00:04:49,085
If you'd be so kind
as to show me where
the car is, please.

51
00:04:49,155 --> 00:04:53,057
That's the car over there,
miss. The black car
with the white wheels.

52
00:04:55,528 --> 00:04:57,462
I'll go and get my bag.
Very good, miss.

53
00:05:00,066 --> 00:05:03,467
Connie. Connie.!
They didn't come?

54
00:05:03,536 --> 00:05:05,902
No.
Oh, Connie,
change your mind.

55
00:05:05,972 --> 00:05:08,941
Spend the summer
with us on the lake.
We have a houseboat.

56
00:05:09,008 --> 00:05:12,910
I'd love to, Marcia, but
they've done so much for me,
you know?

57
00:05:17,016 --> 00:05:21,282
Connie, when you go
to New York, there's a boy...
Sally, I have to hurry.

58
00:05:21,354 --> 00:05:23,652
Where do you think
you're going?
I have to change.

59
00:05:23,723 --> 00:05:26,851
You promised to sing.
Toni, I can't, really.

60
00:05:26,926 --> 00:05:29,258
What do you think of that?
She refuses to sing.

61
00:05:29,329 --> 00:05:33,095
[Chattering]
Let's go to the music room.
Come on!

62
00:05:33,166 --> 00:05:34,895
[Chattering
Continues]
[Knocking]

63
00:05:34,967 --> 00:05:36,901
Yes?
What is it?

64
00:05:36,969 --> 00:05:40,029
May we use the piano,
Miss Wiggins?
What for?

65
00:05:40,106 --> 00:05:43,200
Connie's gonna sing for us.

66
00:05:43,276 --> 00:05:45,267
All right.
Go ahead.

67
00:05:45,345 --> 00:05:47,870
Miss Wiggins says
it's all right.
Come on!

68
00:05:47,947 --> 00:05:51,405
The leader of the glee club
always sings the last song.
They're waiting outside...

69
00:05:51,484 --> 00:05:53,782
I don't feel like singing.
Oh, temperamental, eh?

70
00:05:53,853 --> 00:05:55,787
No, I'm not.
What'll it be,
girls?

71
00:05:55,855 --> 00:05:58,949
[Chattering]
Anything you like.

72
00:05:59,025 --> 00:06:02,358
"Home, Sweet Home" for instance.
What about the one
you sang the other day?

73
00:06:02,428 --> 00:06:04,362
All right.

74
00:06:14,140 --> 00:06:19,976
Mid pleasures

75
00:06:20,046 --> 00:06:25,040
And palaces

76
00:06:25,118 --> 00:06:32,650
Though we may roam

77
00:06:32,725 --> 00:06:37,253
Be it ever

78
00:06:37,330 --> 00:06:41,391
So humble

79
00:06:41,467 --> 00:06:45,904
There's no place

80
00:06:45,972 --> 00:06:50,375
Like home

81
00:06:50,443 --> 00:06:58,316
A charm from the skies

82
00:06:58,384 --> 00:07:07,952
Seems to hallow us there

83
00:07:08,027 --> 00:07:16,492
Which seek
through the world

84
00:07:16,569 --> 00:07:26,240
Is ne'er met with
elsewhere

85
00:07:27,547 --> 00:07:35,852
Home, home

86
00:07:35,922 --> 00:07:44,193
Sweet, sweet home

87
00:07:44,263 --> 00:07:54,935
There's no place
like home

88
00:08:01,781 --> 00:08:04,648
Connie.
What is it, Connie?

89
00:08:05,852 --> 00:08:08,446
That's funny.
Connie never cries.

90
00:08:08,521 --> 00:08:10,546
I'm sorry.

91
00:08:10,623 --> 00:08:12,591
Don't you feel well?

92
00:08:13,860 --> 00:08:15,953
Get out.
Go on. Out.

93
00:08:25,037 --> 00:08:27,232
What's all this?

94
00:08:28,708 --> 00:08:30,642
Look up here.

95
00:08:34,981 --> 00:08:38,144
What's the matter
with you?
Nothing.

96
00:08:38,217 --> 00:08:43,416
It's just that
everybody's going home, and...

97
00:08:43,489 --> 00:08:46,822
And?
And I'm leaving mine.

98
00:08:49,195 --> 00:08:51,129
I thought so.

99
00:08:51,197 --> 00:08:52,858
Crying your eyes out...

100
00:08:52,932 --> 00:08:56,265
just because
you don't have a home
of your own to go to.

101
00:08:56,335 --> 00:08:59,862
Or a mother and father
to tell you how pretty
and clever you are.

102
00:08:59,939 --> 00:09:03,306
Ohh. Poor little thing.

103
00:09:03,376 --> 00:09:07,369
You've just got a voice
that comes to one in a million.

104
00:09:07,446 --> 00:09:12,179
Straight from God to you...
to you alone.

105
00:09:12,251 --> 00:09:14,742
And you sit there
feeling sorry for yourself.

106
00:09:14,820 --> 00:09:17,152
Yes, you are!
Sorry for yourself!

107
00:09:17,223 --> 00:09:22,217
If I were that kind of girl, you
know what I'd do? I'd stick my
tongue out at myself, like that.

108
00:09:30,670 --> 00:09:34,834
Get away. What's all this?
You've been so wonderful
to me, Miss Wiggins.

109
00:09:38,578 --> 00:09:40,671
You go on up there
to New York...

110
00:09:40,746 --> 00:09:45,012
and make those people love you
as much as we do.

111
00:09:45,084 --> 00:09:48,747
And then, maybe someday,
you'll meet a prince,

112
00:09:48,821 --> 00:09:52,052
and you'll live
happily ever after, hmm?

113
00:09:52,124 --> 00:09:56,185
Those fairy stories
haven't come true for over
a hundred years, Miss Wiggins.

114
00:09:57,463 --> 00:09:59,397
Fiddlesticks!

115
00:09:59,465 --> 00:10:02,798
You just have
to dust 'em off,
streamline 'em a bit.

116
00:10:02,868 --> 00:10:06,360
They'd still be
fairy stories, wouldn't they?
That's all life is.

117
00:10:06,439 --> 00:10:10,933
A fairy story. The trouble
with you young people is you
don't believe in anything.

118
00:10:11,010 --> 00:10:14,878
You're afraid...
afraid of hope,
afraid of happiness.

119
00:10:14,947 --> 00:10:18,508
What's New York?
It's just another town.
It's no bigger than you are.

120
00:10:18,584 --> 00:10:22,520
Go there and laugh in it,
love in it, live in it!
Make it yours!

121
00:10:33,366 --> 00:10:35,300
Hold it,
Miss Clinton.

122
00:10:36,669 --> 00:10:38,603
Thank you.

123
00:10:38,671 --> 00:10:40,832
Blue Boy!
Hold it,
Miss Clinton.

124
00:10:41,907 --> 00:10:43,841
Thank you.
Blue Boy, come on!

125
00:10:45,544 --> 00:10:47,512
Hold it, Miss Clinton.
Thank you.

126
00:10:49,715 --> 00:10:52,377
Hold it,
Miss Clinton.
Thank you.

127
00:10:54,353 --> 00:10:58,847
Isn't that wonderful?
Right in the middle of the air.
What's wonderful about it?

128
00:10:58,924 --> 00:11:00,721
It's like
you were a bird.
It's terrible.

129
00:11:00,793 --> 00:11:03,591
Throw that bathing suit out.
It looks like a flour sack.
Yes, miss.

130
00:11:03,663 --> 00:11:05,597
Get my comb.
Yes, miss.

131
00:11:05,665 --> 00:11:08,998
Send that editor a telegram
telling him he's a darling
for putting me on the cover.

132
00:11:09,068 --> 00:11:13,004
May I fix that spangle?
You should have done it
before I put the dress on.

133
00:11:13,072 --> 00:11:16,508
It wasn't loose then.
Well, hurry up.
Comb these curls out. OIlie!

134
00:11:16,575 --> 00:11:20,272
Just one more!
Can you hold just
a little still, please?

135
00:11:20,346 --> 00:11:23,440
Give me that comb.
You can pull on it.
It won't come off.

136
00:11:23,516 --> 00:11:26,917
I didn't want to hurt you.
Get my perfume,
the Clair de Lune Bleu.

137
00:11:26,986 --> 00:11:28,920
Yes, miss.
Is Mother ready?

138
00:11:28,988 --> 00:11:30,922
I got her done
an hour ago.
What's she wearing?

139
00:11:30,990 --> 00:11:32,924
A new one
from Hendricks.
What's it like?

140
00:11:32,992 --> 00:11:36,291
You don't have to worry.
It's nothing like yours.
Which one did you say?

141
00:11:36,362 --> 00:11:38,523
Clair de Lune Bleu.
[Mispronounces]
Clair de Lune Blee.

142
00:11:38,597 --> 00:11:41,657
Bleu. Bleu!
Blue. Blur!

143
00:11:41,734 --> 00:11:44,897
That isn't right,
but you're getting warm.
Oh, thank you, miss.

144
00:11:44,970 --> 00:11:47,268
Here's your coat,
Miss Barbara.
Bring it along.

145
00:11:47,339 --> 00:11:50,570
Which flowers would you like?
I don't care.
Any of them.

146
00:11:50,643 --> 00:11:52,611
These would look nice on you.

147
00:11:52,678 --> 00:11:55,203
They're terrible.
Give me the gardenias.
Yes, Miss Barbara.

148
00:11:55,281 --> 00:11:58,114
Call me at noon tomorrow
and be sure that I get up.
Yes, Miss Barbara.

149
00:11:58,184 --> 00:12:02,314
And call that Swedish girl...
foot massage in the morning.
You shouldn't dance so much.

150
00:12:02,388 --> 00:12:04,322
If Mr. Warrington calls,
tell him to call back.

151
00:12:04,390 --> 00:12:06,881
If Mr. Patton calls,
tell him I have smallpox.

152
00:12:06,959 --> 00:12:09,553
Yes, miss.
A headache
for Mr. Patton.

153
00:12:09,628 --> 00:12:11,892
Where's my bag?
Oh, I forgot it.

154
00:12:11,964 --> 00:12:14,432
Well, get it.

155
00:12:14,500 --> 00:12:17,867
Mother! I'm ready!
Where's Mother, Walter?

156
00:12:17,937 --> 00:12:20,303
Are you ready?
All but one cuff link.

157
00:12:20,372 --> 00:12:24,604
Mother, please!
Oh, my darling child.

158
00:12:24,677 --> 00:12:29,171
You look so sweet!
And that color's
so good for you too.

159
00:12:29,248 --> 00:12:33,048
Or maybe you're good
for the color. I always say
the woman makes the clothes...

160
00:12:33,119 --> 00:12:35,713
Let's get started, hmm?
Even Walter's ready.

161
00:12:35,788 --> 00:12:38,916
Ready and rarin' to go.
We can't go
for quite a while yet.

162
00:12:38,991 --> 00:12:40,925
Oh, good.
What's
the matter now?

163
00:12:40,993 --> 00:12:44,019
George and Terry aren't back
with your cousin yet.
They have the car.

164
00:12:44,096 --> 00:12:46,189
Let's take one of
the other cars.
Which one?

165
00:12:46,265 --> 00:12:50,725
The sedan is waiting for
your father at his office;
my town car's in the garage;

166
00:12:50,803 --> 00:12:54,671
and the big town car
we can't use because the
second chauffeur's off today.

167
00:12:54,740 --> 00:12:58,699
You know, the one who was born
in February. What's his name?
Nick, for Nicholas.

168
00:12:58,778 --> 00:13:03,545
I can't be more than an hour
and a half late for Wilma's party!
She's one of my personal friends.

169
00:13:03,616 --> 00:13:06,210
Why did that child
have to graduate today?

170
00:13:06,285 --> 00:13:09,743
- Graduations are important.
- What's more important to me...

171
00:13:09,822 --> 00:13:12,347
is that Wilma
will think I'm deliberately
sabotaging her party.

172
00:13:12,424 --> 00:13:15,450
Oh, if that's
the case, perhaps we'd
better take a taxi.

173
00:13:15,528 --> 00:13:18,463
That's idiotic.
No one can get
comfortable in a taxi.

174
00:13:18,531 --> 00:13:22,558
- If you'd learn to drive, we
wouldn't have to ride in them.
- Driving is work.

175
00:13:22,635 --> 00:13:25,968
Not as much work
as walking, perhaps,
but still work.

176
00:13:26,038 --> 00:13:29,838
Walter! You came that close
to making an epigram!

177
00:13:29,909 --> 00:13:32,036
You know...
Here they are,
Miss Barbara.

178
00:13:32,111 --> 00:13:34,341
This one matches everything.
Doesn't match
anything.

179
00:13:34,413 --> 00:13:37,405
Throw it out.
Now run outside and see
if you can find a taxi.

180
00:13:37,483 --> 00:13:42,318
- Can you whistle, Agnes?
- You mean like this?
[Whistling]

181
00:13:42,388 --> 00:13:44,652
Don't ever
do that, Agnes.
Well, I'm sorry...

182
00:13:44,723 --> 00:13:47,021
Will you please
get that cab!
Get my coat, please.

183
00:13:47,092 --> 00:13:51,358
In the future, I hope someone
will have enough sense to keep
at least one chauffeur around.

184
00:13:51,430 --> 00:13:55,093
- [Walter] Ditto.
- [Mother] It's all
Mother's fault, I know...

185
00:13:55,167 --> 00:13:57,829
Here they are!

186
00:13:57,903 --> 00:13:59,837
Hello...
Where have you been?

187
00:13:59,905 --> 00:14:02,465
I'm sorry
we're so late.
We had a flat tire.

188
00:14:02,541 --> 00:14:05,738
On an $8,000 automobile?
Impossible!

189
00:14:05,811 --> 00:14:09,440
- [Walter]
We almost had to take a taxi.
- I'm very sorry, Mr. Walter.

190
00:14:09,515 --> 00:14:12,951
- Tell me about the flat
in the morning, Terry.
- But I thought...

191
00:14:13,018 --> 00:14:16,852
When you're going touring again,
be sure there's somebody here
to drive for us.

192
00:14:16,922 --> 00:14:19,584
Mrs. Clinton,
your flowers!
What's the matter with my...

193
00:14:19,658 --> 00:14:21,592
Connie!

194
00:14:21,660 --> 00:14:23,685
Hello.

195
00:14:23,762 --> 00:14:27,789
Oh, my baby!
I'm so glad to see you!

196
00:14:27,867 --> 00:14:32,804
Barbara, you haven't
said a word to Connie.
Happy you managed to get here.

197
00:14:32,872 --> 00:14:36,433
- Walter, what have you
to say to your cousin?
- Hi.

198
00:14:36,508 --> 00:14:38,533
- [Connie] Hello.
- [Barbara] We have to run.

199
00:14:38,611 --> 00:14:42,012
I'll start your horoscope
first thing in the morning.

200
00:14:42,081 --> 00:14:44,743
Do you
still sing?
Yes, I do.

201
00:14:44,817 --> 00:14:48,275
[Muttering]
George, the minute
Mr. Clinton comes in...

202
00:14:48,354 --> 00:14:51,551
By the time we get
there, there won't be
a photographer left!

203
00:14:51,624 --> 00:14:54,559
Good-bye, Connie.
Good-bye, good-bye,
good-bye!

204
00:14:58,664 --> 00:15:00,598
I'll show you
to your room, miss.

205
00:15:02,268 --> 00:15:04,202
Please come this way.

206
00:15:08,173 --> 00:15:11,973
What time do you think
UncleJim will be home?
You mean Mr. Clinton, miss?

207
00:15:12,044 --> 00:15:15,445
Yes.
The goings
and comings of this family
are none of my affair.

208
00:15:15,514 --> 00:15:18,972
Though I might say
if they're out,
Mr. Clinton usually is here.

209
00:15:19,051 --> 00:15:22,282
If they're here,
Mr. Clinton usually is out.

210
00:15:23,756 --> 00:15:25,280
This way, miss.

211
00:15:31,130 --> 00:15:33,155
Here's your room, miss.

212
00:15:42,675 --> 00:15:45,075
Shall I put
the window down, miss?

213
00:15:45,144 --> 00:15:48,272
Hmm?
I said shall I
put the window down?

214
00:15:48,347 --> 00:15:51,908
No, thank you.
It's all right.
May I help you unpack, miss?

215
00:15:51,984 --> 00:15:55,112
I think I can do it
myself, thank you.
Will there be anything else?

216
00:15:55,187 --> 00:15:57,121
No, thank you.
Very well, miss.

217
00:15:57,189 --> 00:16:00,420
There'll be a light supper
served in the dining room
as soon as you are ready.

218
00:16:00,492 --> 00:16:03,723
