Is there anything
you want before you
go to bed, child?

296
00:21:54,780 --> 00:21:58,238
We've got a big watermelon
in the icebox.

297
00:21:58,317 --> 00:22:02,117
No, thank you.
Don't start taking them
too seriously, miss.

298
00:22:02,187 --> 00:22:04,883
You'll get used to them.
Sure. We did.

299
00:22:07,426 --> 00:22:10,088
Good night.
Good night, miss.
Pleasant dreams.

300
00:22:20,105 --> 00:22:23,939
Good afternoon,
Miss Barbara. I've been
waiting for you to wake up.

301
00:22:24,009 --> 00:22:27,240
Your pictures are in
all the morning papers.

302
00:22:27,312 --> 00:22:30,338
What time is it?
It's a little after 2:00.

303
00:22:30,415 --> 00:22:34,681
Which kind? I brought
orange juice, tomato,
grapefruit and grape.

304
00:22:34,753 --> 00:22:38,519
Sauerkraut.
Oh, I never seem
to be able to guess.

305
00:22:38,590 --> 00:22:41,718
I might have known
you'd be in the mood
for sauerkraut today.

306
00:22:41,793 --> 00:22:44,091
When Mr. Drake called,
I told him...

307
00:22:44,162 --> 00:22:46,562
Who called?
Mr. Drake.
He called twice.

308
00:22:46,631 --> 00:22:49,862
Why didn't you wake me up?
I tried to,
both times.

309
00:22:49,935 --> 00:22:53,268
- You did not.
- Oh, yes, I did.
The pillow the first time.

310
00:22:53,338 --> 00:22:55,465
You threw the alarm clock
the second time.

311
00:22:55,540 --> 00:22:58,134
Where'd he call from?
Right here. Just
got back in town.

312
00:22:58,210 --> 00:23:00,940
- What'd he say?
- He wanted you to go riding...

313
00:23:01,012 --> 00:23:04,277
with he and Miss Flourney
and Miss Van Everett
and a lot of people.

314
00:23:04,349 --> 00:23:07,944
They were leaving
at 2:30 sharp.
I'll never get there by 2:30.

315
00:23:08,019 --> 00:23:09,953
Couldn't you telephone him
and ask him to wait?

316
00:23:10,021 --> 00:23:11,955
And make him think
I'm running after him?

317
00:23:12,023 --> 00:23:14,992
I'd run after him.
Papers say he's the catch
of the season.

318
00:23:15,060 --> 00:23:18,154
If I could only stop him
from leaving 'til I get there.
I have an idea.

319
00:23:18,230 --> 00:23:21,529
If you'd called me
when he phoned, you
wouldn't need any ideas.

320
00:23:21,600 --> 00:23:24,797
It's a good idea,
really it is.
I'm sure it is.

321
00:23:24,870 --> 00:23:29,273
I could hurry out to the club,
see Mr. Drake and faint.
Have these shined.

322
00:23:29,341 --> 00:23:32,105
I could throw myself
under his horse's hooves.

323
00:23:32,177 --> 00:23:35,237
I wouldn't mind
doing it for you...
Get that cousin of mine.

324
00:23:35,313 --> 00:23:38,908
If she isn't here by the time
I count ten, you're fired.
Yes, miss!

325
00:23:42,220 --> 00:23:44,085
Miss Connie!
What is it?

326
00:23:44,156 --> 00:23:47,648
Miss Barbara wants you
this minute. Please hurry.
Yes, all right, Agnes.

327
00:23:48,894 --> 00:23:51,192
Miss Connie'll be
right in.
Oh, I am in.

328
00:23:51,263 --> 00:23:54,232
Oh, you are.
Never mind.

329
00:24:01,239 --> 00:24:05,676
Yes, Barbara?
Some friends
of mine are going riding at
the country club in a half hour.

330
00:24:05,744 --> 00:24:08,975
I want you to delay their start
'til I get there, understand?
You mean stop them?

331
00:24:09,047 --> 00:24:11,538
- At least stop Ted Drake.
- I don't even know him.

332
00:24:11,616 --> 00:24:13,584
You know what
he looks like.
No.

333
00:24:13,652 --> 00:24:16,712
The most notable
young man in New York.
You must have seen his picture.

334
00:24:16,788 --> 00:24:20,315
I don't think so.
Well, you'll find one
in that drawer.

335
00:24:20,392 --> 00:24:23,486
Which one?
The top drawer.

336
00:24:23,562 --> 00:24:27,293
In the dresser?
Yes. Just open it.
You'll find it.

337
00:24:27,365 --> 00:24:29,697
I don't see
any picture here.

338
00:24:29,768 --> 00:24:33,864
Oh, you don't see any picture.
I told you it was there.
Why don't you look for it?

339
00:24:33,939 --> 00:24:37,670
- What do you think this is?
And please hurry!
- Oh, I think...

340
00:24:37,742 --> 00:24:42,111
What'll I say to him?
I don't care what you say
as long as you keep him there.

341
00:24:42,180 --> 00:24:44,410
And be sure
he doesn't know
I sent you.

342
00:24:44,483 --> 00:24:48,510
- I don't think
I can do it, Barbara.
- All right, don't then.

343
00:24:48,587 --> 00:24:51,681
- Oh, I mean...
- After all this family's
done for you,

344
00:24:51,756 --> 00:24:54,691
the first time we ask you
to do something for us,
you refuse.

345
00:24:54,759 --> 00:24:57,592
Oh, I'll do it then.
I don't know what to do.

346
00:24:57,662 --> 00:25:00,597
Faint. Make him revive you.
Fall in front ofhim.
Steal his horse.

347
00:25:00,665 --> 00:25:03,395
I don't care, as long as
he's there when I get there.
And hurry!

348
00:25:08,540 --> 00:25:11,236
Off for a little stroll,
Miss Connie?
Yes. I mean no.

349
00:25:11,309 --> 00:25:14,608
I'll need the car. Oh,
my hat. I left it in there.
I'll get the car.

350
00:25:14,679 --> 00:25:16,738
- Thank you.
I'm in an awful hurry.
- [Walter] Why?

351
00:25:16,815 --> 00:25:21,548
I have to stop Ted Drake's horse
at the country club for Barbara.
Oh, not his horse. Him.

352
00:25:21,620 --> 00:25:24,214
But he'll be on it.
You know what I mean.
Perfectly.

353
00:25:24,289 --> 00:25:28,089
I have to run now.
Good-bye.
Connie,
give me a cigarette, please.

354
00:25:28,159 --> 00:25:30,753
Oh, yes.
When were you born,
Connie?

355
00:25:30,829 --> 00:25:34,595
- December 4th.
- Sagittarius.
Oh, how interesting.

356
00:25:34,666 --> 00:25:37,794
What time
of day?
I don't remember.

357
00:25:37,869 --> 00:25:41,999
I'm going to do your horoscope.
Hurry back, and I'll tell you
all about yourself.

358
00:25:42,073 --> 00:25:44,007
Yes, Aunt Grace.

359
00:25:47,112 --> 00:25:49,774
You'd better wait here.
They might recognize the car.

360
00:25:49,848 --> 00:25:52,578
I'll keep the motor running
in case we have to make
a quick getaway.

361
00:25:52,651 --> 00:25:54,585
I'm awfully nervous.
Don't worry.

362
00:25:54,653 --> 00:25:56,587
Mr. Drake?
The horses ready, Dan?

363
00:25:56,655 --> 00:25:59,283
Yes, sir,
all 13 of them.
Thirteen's bad luck.

364
00:25:59,357 --> 00:26:02,087
We're not
superstitious, are we?
Let's wait for Barbara.

365
00:26:02,160 --> 00:26:06,859
It's only a little after 2:30.
If we wait for her, we'll have
to make this a moonlight ride.

366
00:26:06,932 --> 00:26:10,299
She'll probably just arrive
by the time we get back.
Let's go.

367
00:26:10,368 --> 00:26:14,862
I think if we go off without
her, it'll be good for her.
I think we should wait.

368
00:26:17,742 --> 00:26:19,573
Uh... Uh.

369
00:26:25,283 --> 00:26:27,217
Hey!

370
00:26:29,487 --> 00:26:31,421
Barbara know about
this trip you're taking?

371
00:26:31,489 --> 00:26:34,515
I didn't even tell the family
'til this morning.
When do you leave?

372
00:26:34,593 --> 00:26:38,689
A month. We don't start up
the Amazon 'til late September.
The Amazon's a river, isn't it?

373
00:26:38,763 --> 00:26:41,561
Named after
a tribe of women.
So that's
what's behind this expedition.

374
00:26:41,633 --> 00:26:43,567
Barbara'll
be thrilled.
Are you with us?

375
00:26:43,635 --> 00:26:45,933
No, I'm alone.
How cozy.

376
00:26:47,739 --> 00:26:52,403
Mr. Kirkpatrick.!
Wanted on the telephone.!

377
00:26:54,746 --> 00:26:57,078
All right, Willie.
I'll take it.
Yes, sir.

378
00:26:57,148 --> 00:27:00,117
Won't be a minute.

379
00:27:00,185 --> 00:27:03,211
[Chattering]

380
00:27:06,224 --> 00:27:11,059
Mr. Drake!
Wanted on the telephone!

381
00:27:11,129 --> 00:27:14,326
- That must be Barbara.
- Maybe it's Dad.
You go on along.

382
00:27:14,399 --> 00:27:17,664
- Oh, we'll wait.
- No, go ahead. I'll
meet you at the willows.

383
00:27:17,736 --> 00:27:19,670
Don't be long.
I won't.

384
00:27:40,158 --> 00:27:42,854
Nice horsey.
Don't be afraid.
I'm not gonna hurt you.

385
00:27:42,927 --> 00:27:45,657
I just want
to undo this.

386
00:27:45,730 --> 00:27:48,824
I'm not gonna hurt you.
See? Sugar. Sugar.

387
00:27:48,900 --> 00:27:50,834
Just wanna undo this, see?

388
00:27:51,970 --> 00:27:54,564
That's it.
Come on.
Get the sugar.

389
00:27:54,639 --> 00:27:58,166
Got some more in here.
You can have that when
you get to the barn.

390
00:27:58,243 --> 00:28:00,768
Come on.
Get the sugar.

391
00:28:00,845 --> 00:28:04,872
You can have it all
if you'll just come
to the barn. Come on.

392
00:28:08,353 --> 00:28:10,878
Come on.
I got some more for you.
You like sugar, don't you?

393
00:28:12,691 --> 00:28:15,626
So do I. Come on.
Get the sugar.

394
00:28:15,694 --> 00:28:19,095
That's a good horsey.
Come on. Come on.

395
00:28:19,164 --> 00:28:21,758
Did you call me
to the phone?
No, Mr. Drake.

396
00:28:21,833 --> 00:28:24,563
There's nobody on it.
Somebody called.
I'm sorry, sir.

397
00:28:24,636 --> 00:28:29,369
- What's going on
with that horse?
- Come on.

398
00:28:29,441 --> 00:28:32,842
There's lots more
where this came from.
Come on. That's a boy.

399
00:28:32,911 --> 00:28:35,971
I don't like my horse
to have sugar.
Oh, he likes it.

400
00:28:38,717 --> 00:28:41,242
Hey, Shamrock!
Come here, boy. Hey!

401
00:28:42,654 --> 00:28:47,216
Hey! Hey, Shamrock. Here!
Come back here!

402
00:28:47,292 --> 00:28:49,556
Here, fella, take it easy.

403
00:28:52,864 --> 00:28:54,695
Hey!

404
00:28:59,471 --> 00:29:03,464
The horses have
enough trouble with this jump
without looking out for you.

405
00:29:03,541 --> 00:29:06,271
I fell when you chased me.
I wasn't chasing you.
I was chasing the horse.

406
00:29:06,344 --> 00:29:09,438
Not that way.
Look out!

407
00:29:09,514 --> 00:29:11,573
Let's get out of here
before another horse
takes after you.

408
00:29:11,649 --> 00:29:13,844
What are you tryin' to do,
kill yourself?

409
00:29:13,918 --> 00:29:16,944
Between stuffing my horse
with sugar and making yourself
a steeplechase hazard,

410
00:29:17,021 --> 00:29:19,012
you've had
a pretty busy day.

411
00:29:19,090 --> 00:29:22,856
If one of those jumpers
had been short, you'd really
have something to worry about.

412
00:29:22,927 --> 00:29:26,886
Now run along and try
and keep out of mischief.
[Muttering]

413
00:29:30,235 --> 00:29:32,965
[Crying]

414
00:29:34,139 --> 00:29:37,540
Oh, come on.
You're all right now.

415
00:29:37,609 --> 00:29:40,134
Is there a handkerchief
in there? Let me
get it for you.

416
00:29:40,211 --> 00:29:42,406
It's nothing.
It's just a natural react...

417
00:29:46,684 --> 00:29:49,812
You must like horses
an awful lot.
No, I don't. I just...

418
00:29:49,888 --> 00:29:52,652
You carry a lot
of sugar around.
Oh, that's...

419
00:29:52,724 --> 00:29:54,851
Could you show me the way
out of here, please?

420
00:29:54,926 --> 00:29:57,326
The same way you got in.
I've got friends waiting.

421
00:29:57,395 --> 00:30:00,023
It'd only take
a few minutes.
I'm a little dizzy.

422
00:30:00,098 --> 00:30:05,229
Well, that, young lady, is
a masterpiece of understatement.
You're the dizz...

423
00:30:10,241 --> 00:30:13,233
Now I wonder
what's happened to her.

424
00:30:13,311 --> 00:30:17,042
That's fine. You ought to have
a keeper or a nurse.

425
00:30:17,115 --> 00:30:19,106
Ted!

426
00:30:21,019 --> 00:30:24,216
What are you doing?
The kid's fainted.
She had a bad scare.

427
00:30:24,289 --> 00:30:26,723
Get some water.
I'll take care of her.
Who is she?

428
00:30:26,791 --> 00:30:29,783
I don't know. You
better get some water.
I'll be right back.

429
00:30:33,932 --> 00:30:35,832
All right, thanks.

430
00:30:35,900 --> 00:30:39,063
You're welcome.
You didn't have to
kill yourself.

431
00:30:39,137 --> 00:30:41,901
You told me to keep him here.
I didn't tell you
to hang on his neck.

432
00:30:41,973 --> 00:30:45,807
I didn't. He held me up...
Go on home.
Don't let anybody see you.

433
00:30:45,877 --> 00:30:48,539
I just wanted to thank him.
He was awfully nice.

434
00:30:48,613 --> 00:30:50,979
Do you want to spoil
everything now?
Oh, no.

435
00:30:51,049 --> 00:30:54,348
Then get out of here
before he gets back.
Hurry up!
Barbara!

436
00:30:54,419 --> 00:30:57,786
If you'd only...
Will you do what
you're told for a change?

437
00:30:59,457 --> 00:31:01,584
I only want
to thank him...
I'll thank him.

438
00:31:01,659 --> 00:31:04,093
Go home before
he sees you again.
But...

439
00:31:08,233 --> 00:31:10,827
Will you get
my horse out, Frankie?
Yes, Miss Clinton. Right away.

440
00:31:10,902 --> 00:31:13,268
What's happened
to our patient?
Oh, that little brat.

441
00:31:13,338 --> 00:31:17,536
- She ran off like a rabbit.
- She's a funny kid.
Who do you think she is?

442
00:31:17,609 --> 00:31:20,373
You don't know?
The first time
I ever saw her...

443
00:31:20,445 --> 00:31:22,538
was when I caught her
feeding sugar to my horse.

444
00:31:22,614 --> 00:31:25,048
A likely story. Girls
just chase you around.

445
00:31:25,116 --> 00:31:27,880
- Hello, Wilma.
- I'm so glad you
finally got here.

446
00:31:27,952 --> 00:31:31,046
- The gang went on, Ted.
- I'll get my horse
and be right back.

447
00:31:31,122 --> 00:31:34,114
You look lovely.
If I slept this late,
I'd be a sight.

448
00:31:34,192 --> 00:31:37,093
You're priceless.
You always look the same
no matter what you do.

449
00:31:37,161 --> 00:31:39,686
Mademoiselle Bristo says that
whenever she gives me a facial.

450
00:31:39,764 --> 00:31:42,699
You ought to try her.
She's marvelous at
taking bad lines out.

451
00:31:42,767 --> 00:31:45,998
- She must be miraculous.
- You'd be surprised what
she can do for your nerves.

452
00:31:46,070 --> 00:31:49,039
That's where you
plump people are lucky.
You have no nerves.

453
00:31:49,107 --> 00:31:53,066
Here you are, Miss Clinton.
Be careful. That hat might
make him a little skittish.

454
00:31:53,144 --> 00:31:56,443
Don't worry about the General.
He has better taste
than most people.

455
00:31:56,514 --> 00:31:59,847
- Horses always know
more than their riders.
- Which path do we take?

456
00:31:59,918 --> 00:32:03,354
The upper one is shorter,
but there are too many
jumps for Barbara.

457
00:32:03,421 --> 00:32:06,390
Don't worry about me.
The upper road is
ten minutes faster.

458
00:32:06,457 --> 00:32:09,620
Ted and I will
take the lower one
and race you there.

459
00:32:09,694 --> 00:32:12,458
All right, let's go.
Careful with
those jumps, dear.

460
00:32:23,441 --> 00:32:26,501
Barbara!
How nice of you
to hurry home for tea.

461
00:32:26,577 --> 00:32:29,978
Who wants tea?
Why, dear pet,
what happened to you?

462
00:32:30,048 --> 00:32:33,040
Wilma Van Everett.
What did
little Wilma do?

463
00:32:33,117 --> 00:32:35,051
I'd like to kill
"little" Wilma.

464
00:32:35,119 --> 00:32:38,555
What did she do, dear?
Something horrible,
I trust?

465
00:32:38,623 --> 00:32:43,424
She succeeded in making herself
ridiculous in front of everybody
at the club this afternoon.

466
00:32:43,494 --> 00:32:45,792
She acted like a fool
over Ted Drake.

467
00:32:45,863 --> 00:32:48,195
That's terrible!
Put them there, Connie.
All right.

468
00:32:48,266 --> 00:32:51,463
You certainly covered
yourself with glory today.
I only tried to...

469
00:32:51,536 --> 00:32:54,630
You tried brilliantly.
Never mind. Tell
your story, Barbara.

470
00:32:54,706 --> 00:32:57,004
You wouldn't believe it
unless you were there.
I would.

471
00:32:57,075 --> 00:32:59,009
She only advertised
to everybody present...

472
00:32:59,077 --> 00:33:01,602
that she was
head-over-heels
in love with Ted.

473
00:33:01,679 --> 00:33:03,909
That's silly!
It was revolting.
Why?

474
00:33:03,982 --> 00:33:08,009
- Girls fall in love
with Ted all the time.
- She only just met him!

475
00:33:08,086 --> 00:33:11,647
Love at first sight.
I've read about it.
It's very rare.

476
00:33:11,723 --> 00:33:16,092
A Leo and Sagittarius might
do it if Saturn were in accord.
Her birthday is...

477
00:33:16,160 --> 00:33:19,095
- December 4th.
- How do you know?

478
00:33:19,163 --> 00:33:21,961
I certainly
should know.
You know her, do you?

479
00:33:22,033 --> 00:33:24,558
What are you...
Everybody knows
Wilma Van Everett.

480
00:33:24,635 --> 00:33:28,036
She gets twice as much
publicity as you do.
She does not.!

481
00:33:28,106 --> 00:33:30,040
Does.
Doesn't.
Mother!

482
00:33:30,108 --> 00:33:34,909
Walter! Isn't that strange?
That's the same birthday as you,
isn't it, Connie?

483
00:33:34,979 --> 00:33:38,312
Yes, that's right.
December 4th.

484
00:33:38,383 --> 00:33:41,910
[Barbara] I'm going to fix
Miss Van Everett. I'll see her
at the Drakes'party.

485
00:33:41,986 --> 00:33:44,580
[Grace] Are the Drakes
going to have a party?
[Barbara] On the 29th.

486
00:33:44,655 --> 00:33:48,751
I'll have something figured out.
Everybody will know about it
because everybody will be there.

487
00:33:48,826 --> 00:33:52,887
Everybody?
Connie, what are
you going to wear?

488
00:33:52,964 --> 00:33:55,990
To the party you mean?
Oh, I haven't been in...

489
00:33:56,067 --> 00:33:59,264
I'm not going, am I?

490
00:33:59,337 --> 00:34:04,400
- Of course you are. Sister
just said everybody's going.
- I haven't... I'd have to wear...

491
00:34:04,475 --> 00:34:07,569
- It's formal, isn't it?
- Barbara's probably got
something upstairs...

492
00:34:07,645 --> 00:34:09,875
that would suit you
perfect.

493
00:34:09,947 --> 00:34:12,507
How about it?
And have people say
she's wearing my castoffs?

494
00:34:12,583 --> 00:34:16,178
- We wouldn't want
that, would we?
- No. Of course not.

495
00:34:16,254 --> 00:34:18,882
But I could wear...
Mother...
Wait. You're interrupting.

496
00:34:18,956 --> 00:34:22,824
You could what?
I could wear my
graduation dress.

497
00:34:22,894 --> 00:34:25,795
It's very pretty,
and it's long and white.
All white.

498
00:34:25,863 --> 00:34:29,094
White's a pretty color.
It isn't
a garden party.

499
00:34:29,167 --> 00:34:32,830
I could make it into
an evening dress. I'd just
have to fix the sleeves...

500
00:34:32,904 --> 00:34:36,362
See how simple it is?
I'll start figuring out
what to do with it.

501
00:34:36,441 --> 00:34:38,875
And thank you.
Thank you very much.

502
00:34:38,943 --> 00:34:40,877
I took sewing
in school, you know.

503
00:34:40,945 --> 00:34:44,346
I'll have to fix the skirt
a little, and maybe I can
fix the neck.

504
00:34:44,415 --> 00:34:46,576
We're not going
to drag her to the ball.

505
00:34:46,651 --> 00:34:50,883
If she fixes her dress, I'm
afraid we'll have to take her.
You can't get out of it.

506
00:34:50,955 --> 00:34:53,890
Don't think I'm going to be
bothered with her
once she gets there.

507
00:34:53,958 --> 00:34:56,791
Be nice to her at the ball,
sister, or people will have
an excuse...

508
00:34:56,861 --> 00:35:01,355
to say some of the things
they've been thinking
about you for years.

509
00:35:04,769 --> 00:35:07,761
I'm going to
the Drakes' ball.
What are you gonna do?

510
00:35:07,839 --> 00:35:10,137
I'm going to
the Drakes' ball.
No foolin'!

511
00:35:10,208 --> 00:35:14,440
Absolutely. I have to cut
the sleeves out. I have to
make this into an evening dress.

512
00:35:14,512 --> 00:35:17,242
- Does the duchess
know you're going?
- Barbara? Certainly.

513
00:35:17,315 --> 00:35:21,615
They only just told me
about it. I didn't
dream I was going.

514
00:35:21,686 --> 00:35:25,349
That's wonderful, Miss Connie.
I'm so happy for you.
Thank you, Agnes.

515
00:35:25,423 --> 00:35:29,985
I do want to look pretty
when he sees me this time...
when people see me.

516
00:35:30,061 --> 00:35:32,996
I mean...
You know.
When who sees you
this time?

517
00:35:33,064 --> 00:35:37,694
Everybody. Everybody in
New York's going to be there.
What slippers shall I wear?

518
00:35:37,768 --> 00:35:39,702
Who's the "he" you were
just talkin' about?

519
00:35:39,770 --> 00:35:44,070
I didn't mean any particular
person. Do you think these
slippers'll be all right?

520
00:35:44,142 --> 00:35:48,101
Maybe if I cut the neckline
lower and sort of
flare out the skirt.

521
00:35:48,179 --> 00:35:51,740
Miss OIlie could tell you.
She makes all her clothes.
Do you think she'd mind?

522
00:35:51,816 --> 00:35:55,684
Oh, no, OIlie loves to...
I didn't know you knew
any "he" in New York.

523
00:35:55,753 --> 00:35:59,052
I don't know any "he"...
I mean anybody.

524
00:35:59,123 --> 00:36:02,354
Just because you see a person
doesn't mean you know a person.

525
00:36:02,426 --> 00:36:05,327
Let's go ask OIlie
about the dress.
She's in the kitchen.

526
00:36:06,531 --> 00:36:09,227
Miss Connie's going to the...
George told us.

527
00:36:09,300 --> 00:36:12,531
Did they tell you about it?
I couldn't help
overhearing.

528
00:36:12,603 --> 00:36:15,128
I'm almost as happy
as if I were going myself.

529
00:36:15,206 --> 00:36:18,505
I've never been to
a big party like this before.
It'll be a great night.

530
00:36:18,576 --> 00:36:20,874
It certainly will.
Is that the dress
you want to make over?

531
00:36:20,945 --> 00:36:25,609
Yes, Agnes said you might
help me. May I put it here?
Put it anywhere.

532
00:36:25,683 --> 00:36:29,517
It still has sleeves.
I thought if we'd only use
the skirt and make a bodice...

533
00:36:29,587 --> 00:36:31,452
and then flare the skirt...

534
00:36:31,522 --> 00:36:34,548
Don't mind me.
I only eat here.

535
00:36:34,625 --> 00:36:39,153
That's my brother Mike.
This is Miss Connie. You know,
I told you about her singing.

536
00:36:39,230 --> 00:36:42,097
- How do you do?
- Don't let me stop
the operation.

537
00:36:42,166 --> 00:36:45,397
I'm used to blood.
Have you any more
of this material?

538
00:36:45,469 --> 00:36:48,233
No, but I have
a yard of silver lace.
Maybe you can use that.

539
00:36:48,306 --> 00:36:51,070
Only a yard?
Yes, but it's very pretty.
I'll run get it.

540
00:36:51,142 --> 00:36:53,667
The design's lovely.
You'll see.

541
00:36:53,744 --> 00:36:56,679
It's a good thing
it wasn't one of the others
that found you here.

542
00:36:56,747 --> 00:36:58,942
They would have
called the police.
Fine crack.

543
00:36:59,016 --> 00:37:01,951
Think you can fix it up?
I can try. I wish
the waist was higher.

544
00:37:02,019 --> 00:37:06,422
Hold this.
Gotta look beautiful at that
ball for a very special reason.

545
00:37:06,490 --> 00:37:09,288
What's his name?
What do you think I am,
a tattletale?

546
00:37:09,360 --> 00:37:10,987
How about hoops?
Never mind hoops.

547
00:37:11,062 --> 00:37:14,259
You better watch that roast or
we'll have a terrible dinner.
Oh, my gracious!

548
00:37:14,332 --> 00:37:17,733
Well done might be all right
for the family, but I like
my beef rare.

549
00:37:17,802 --> 00:37:20,669
What can I do?
Why don't you put
some feathers on it?

550
00:37:20,738 --> 00:37:24,139
How about those things
on the shoulders like
football players wear?

551
00:37:24,208 --> 00:37:27,143
I just don't know
what to do.
I can tell you.

552
00:37:27,211 --> 00:37:30,442
- This oughta be good.
- You take this dress...

553
00:37:30,514 --> 00:37:32,778
and first,
you hide it away,

554
00:37:32,850 --> 00:37:35,410
and then you go out
and buy her a whole
new outfit.

555
00:37:35,486 --> 00:37:37,386
With what?
With money.

556
00:37:37,455 --> 00:37:39,650
Whose money?
My money and your money.

557
00:37:39,724 --> 00:37:42,124
And mine too.
Count me in.
And me.

558
00:37:42,193 --> 00:37:45,060
Only goes to show
you don't get nothin'
for nothin' in this world,

559
00:37:45,129 --> 00:37:47,063
not even from
your own sister.

560
00:37:47,131 --> 00:37:49,065
How much?

561
00:38:00,811 --> 00:38:05,908
It wasn't hard to do at all,
miss. I just bought another
yard or two of that lace.

562
00:38:05,983 --> 00:38:08,076
Every bit of it
seems different.

563
00:38:08,152 --> 00:38:11,053
When I remodel a dress,
I really remodel it.

564
00:38:11,122 --> 00:38:14,421
The slippers just arrived.
I had to bring them up and
see how she looked.

565
00:38:14,492 --> 00:38:16,960
It's a perfect fit.
It's really magnificent.

566
00:38:17,028 --> 00:38:20,020
I still can't believe
it's the same dress.
OIlie did a lot of work on it.

567
00:38:20,097 --> 00:38:21,997
May I put these on,
please?

568
00:38:22,066 --> 00:38:25,763
These aren't my slippers.
Well, you see,
we took them out to a man...

569
00:38:25,836 --> 00:38:27,701
to have some silver
put on them.

570
00:38:27,772 --> 00:38:29,569
You know, like...
Like dyeing.

571
00:38:29,640 --> 00:38:33,872
While he was doing it,
he spilled it all inside,
and you couldn't have worn them.

572
00:38:33,944 --> 00:38:37,573
- So he only did what was right.
- He got you a new pair.

573
00:38:37,648 --> 00:38:39,616
He shouldn't have
done that.
He's insured.

574
00:38:39,684 --> 00:38:41,743
Do they feel
all right?
Why, yes.

575
00:38:41,819 --> 00:38:46,483
They're just a little bit new,
but they fit perfectly.
[Knocking]

576
00:38:46,557 --> 00:38:49,253
Come in.
I just wanted to see
how you looked.

577
00:38:49,327 --> 00:38:52,524
You couldn't even tell
it was the same dress.
You look like a picture!

578
00:38:52,596 --> 00:38:55,531
I don't see how...
OIlie must have worked
day and night...

579
00:38:55,599 --> 00:38:57,829
Oh, turn around
a minute.
How does the skirt hang?

580
00:38:57,902 --> 00:39:00,200
Perfect!
Why don't you go
in Miss Barbara's room?

581
00:39:00,271 --> 00:39:02,398
You can see how
you really look.
That's a good idea.

582
00:39:02,473 --> 00:39:05,704
I'll be back
in a minute.
Oh, just a second.

583
00:39:07,712 --> 00:39:10,340
Thank you.
These just came
for you, miss.

584
00:39:10,414 --> 00:39:12,177
How lovely!
Who sent it?

585
00:39:12,249 --> 00:39:16,413
There wasn't any card.
Probably some admirer who knew
you were going to the ball.

586
00:39:16,487 --> 00:39:19,012
Oh, you mean...
No.

587
00:39:19,090 --> 00:39:21,388
How could he...
Oh, I don't think so.

588
00:39:21,459 --> 00:39:24,428
They match your dress.
Isn't that nice?
[Barbara] Ollie.!

589
00:39:24,495 --> 00:39:27,487
- Oh, I've been expecting that.
- OIlie, where have you been?

590
00:39:27,565 --> 00:39:30,056
I want a large chiffon
handkerchief, black.
The bracelet.

591
00:39:30,134 --> 00:39:33,501
Yes, miss.

592
00:39:33,571 --> 00:39:37,769
Pardon me a minute.
I want to see how the skirt
hangs in the back.

593
00:39:37,842 --> 00:39:39,810
I think it's
all right, don't you?

594
00:39:39,877 --> 00:39:43,870
- What school did you
graduate from in that dress?
- We fixed it up. You like it?

595
00:39:43,948 --> 00:39:47,384
The skirt hangs perfectly.
Oh, I forgot my locket.
I better go get it.

596
00:39:47,451 --> 00:39:49,385
You look
very nice too.
Thanks.

597
00:39:49,453 --> 00:39:52,581
I don't think
I'd look so good
in black.

598
00:39:52,656 --> 00:39:56,114
You'd better hurry.
We don't want to be too late.

599
00:39:56,193 --> 00:39:59,890
Did you see that?
Yes, miss. I think
she looks very nice.

600
00:39:59,964 --> 00:40:03,297
Has she gone crazy,
storming in here,
patronizing me?

601
00:40:03,367 --> 00:40:06,564
Oh, no, she's
just so thrilled about
going to the Drakes'.

602
00:40:06,637 --> 00:40:09,333
She's taking
a lot for granted.
She isn't there yet.

603
00:40:09,407 --> 00:40:11,568
Bring my wrap.
Yes, miss.

604
00:40:12,810 --> 00:40:16,439
Did you hear that?
Yes!
What'd she say?

605
00:40:16,514 --> 00:40:20,211
Mother, are you ready?
Yes, dear. I was looking
up the stars for tonight.

606
00:40:20,284 --> 00:40:22,218
We're going to have
a marvelous evening.
I doubt that.

607
00:40:22,286 --> 00:40:26,347
You mustn't doubt the stars.
They control your destiny,
whether you like it or not.

608
00:40:26,424 --> 00:40:29,689
Ready? That's a very
smart gown, Aunt Grace.
Thank you.

609
00:40:29,760 --> 00:40:32,558
Have you seen
my new dress?
Connie, it's amazing!

610
00:40:32,630 --> 00:40:34,689
My wrap, please.
Mother, can we go?

611
00:40:34,765 --> 00:40:37,427
Certainly. George,
is the car waiting?
Yes, Miss Connie.

612
00:40:37,501 --> 00:40:39,435
Your cigarette case.
Where did
you find it?

613
00:40:39,503 --> 00:40:42,199
In Mr. Clinton's study.
Oh, dear, where will I
leave it next?

614
00:40:43,274 --> 00:40:47,176
[Connie] Have you seen the
newspaper? The society page is
full of details about the ball.

615
00:40:47,244 --> 00:40:50,475
It mentioned all
the famous people who
are going to be there.

616
00:40:50,548 --> 00:40:52,482
It's sure to be
a brilliant affair.

617
00:40:52,550 --> 00:40:55,417
I hope they don't
just play rumbas.
You'd prefer waltzes.

618
00:40:55,486 --> 00:40:59,388
I like waltzes.
I do too.
So do I. Dreamy ones.

619
00:40:59,457 --> 00:41:01,322
My wrap.
This one?

620
00:41:01,392 --> 00:41:04,623
No, the other one.
Mother, I think I'll
wear your pearl bracelet.

621
00:41:04,695 --> 00:41:07,687
It goes better
with a black dress.
This isn't mine!

622
00:41:07,765 --> 00:41:11,030
It is tonight.
Tomorrow it goes back
in Cousin Egbert's show window.

623
00:41:11,101 --> 00:41:13,001
Oh, but really...
Shh!

624
00:41:13,070 --> 00:41:16,039
- Shh.
- If Mr. Clinton comes,
tell him we'll be late.

625
00:41:16,106 --> 00:41:19,542
Yes, ma'am.
Suppose UncleJason comes in
from Washington tonight?

626
00:41:19,610 --> 00:41:21,544
What makes you think
he's coming tonight?

627
00:41:21,612 --> 00:41:24,638
Aunt Louise
said yesterday
that he might.
She did?

628
00:41:24,715 --> 00:41:27,843
I forgot to tell you.
Let's hope he doesn't arrive
until tomorrow.

629
00:41:27,918 --> 00:41:31,979
If he does come and there isn't
one member of the family home,
we'll never hear the end of it.

630
00:41:32,056 --> 00:41:35,025
I'll be glad to stay
and welcome him.
He hates the sight of you.

631
00:41:35,092 --> 00:41:36,992
Can't say that
I blame him.
How about Father?

632
00:41:37,061 --> 00:41:40,155
Your father won't be home
until all hours.
It's no great problem.

633
00:41:40,231 --> 00:41:44,190
Connie can stay and sing
to him or something. You
don't mind, do you, Connie?

634
00:41:44,268 --> 00:41:47,203
- Tonight? Now?
- You're dear to do it.

635
00:41:48,839 --> 00:41:52,104
- Y-You mean I'm to wait here?
- Just make our excuses.

636
00:41:52,176 --> 00:41:55,668
And fuss over him
when he arrives.
No.

637
00:41:55,746 --> 00:41:59,204
No. You're not really going
to make me miss the party.

638
00:41:59,283 --> 00:42:01,843
You can't.
That isn't fair.

639
00:42:01,919 --> 00:42:06,686
You could have told me sooner
so I wouldn't plan and...
and wait and...

640
00:42:06,757 --> 00:42:10,022
If you're going to argue
about everything we ask
you to do, I'll stay.

641
00:42:10,094 --> 00:42:12,824
You can't do that.
The Drakes would be offended.

642
00:42:12,897 --> 00:42:15,058
We'll make it up to you, Connie.

643
00:42:15,132 --> 00:42:17,293
Barbara, you're only...

644
00:42:17,368 --> 00:42:20,496
