00:57:16,332 --> 00:57:19,301
And I can tell
by looking at you two
that you're real old friends.

855
00:57:19,369 --> 00:57:21,530
Mr. Drake...
Would you like to dance?

856
00:57:21,604 --> 00:57:24,095
You hear that, Bevans?
Would she like to? What's the
matter with you young fellas?

857
00:57:24,174 --> 00:57:26,938
She'd love to dance.
Yes, I would.

858
00:57:38,087 --> 00:57:40,851
Lovely young lady,
Gerald.
Yes, indeed, Mr. Drake.

859
00:57:40,924 --> 00:57:44,018
I wish that boy of mine
would get interested in a girl
like that and stay home...

860
00:57:44,093 --> 00:57:46,254
instead of hopping off
on that South American thing.

861
00:57:46,329 --> 00:57:48,524
Maybe he will.
Yes, maybe.

862
00:57:48,598 --> 00:57:52,534
What'd you say her name was?
Don't start that!
I don't know!

863
00:58:00,343 --> 00:58:03,403
Oh, I'm sorry.
It's my fault.
I'm used to leading.

864
00:58:03,480 --> 00:58:08,144
At school when just we
girls danced, one led and...
And the other followed.

865
00:58:08,218 --> 00:58:11,745
That's right.
How's your horse?
Shamrock?

866
00:58:11,821 --> 00:58:14,722
Yes. I hope the sugar
didn't make him sick.

867
00:58:16,626 --> 00:58:20,756
What's the matter?
I'm sorry. I was thinking
how different you look.

868
00:58:20,830 --> 00:58:23,958
I'm glad of that.
I didn't see my face
until I got in the car.

869
00:58:24,033 --> 00:58:26,593
You were in a bad way there
for a few minutes.

870
00:58:26,669 --> 00:58:30,230
I didn't thank you for being
so nice about everything and
tell you I was all right.

871
00:58:30,306 --> 00:58:34,402
I figured you were all right
when I heard you'd run away.
I couldn't help that.

872
00:58:34,477 --> 00:58:38,436
Don't, don't ever
run away again
without saying good-bye.

873
00:58:38,515 --> 00:58:40,449
I mean it.

874
00:59:19,589 --> 00:59:22,683
[Orchestra Stops]
[Applause]

875
00:59:27,397 --> 00:59:31,026
[Orchestra]

876
00:59:48,585 --> 00:59:51,748
Too many people here.
Yes.

877
00:59:51,821 --> 00:59:54,790
Let's go outside.
All right.

878
01:00:04,934 --> 01:00:07,869
It isn't too cool for you,
is it?
No, not at all.

879
01:00:07,937 --> 01:00:10,371
If you'd rather go inside...
No.

880
01:00:10,440 --> 01:00:13,034
Maybe you would, though.
I could get your wrap.

881
01:00:13,109 --> 01:00:15,043
Oh, no, really.
I'm all right.

882
01:00:15,111 --> 01:00:17,045
I was...
Do you...

883
01:00:17,113 --> 01:00:19,377
Go ahead.
It was nothing.
What were you going to say?

884
01:00:19,449 --> 01:00:23,408
I was just thinking
I'm leaving here next week.

885
01:00:23,486 --> 01:00:26,944
Are you?
I'm going to South America
with Dr. McKenzie.

886
01:00:27,023 --> 01:00:30,515
You've heard of him,
haven't you?
McKenzie? I think I have.

887
01:00:30,593 --> 01:00:32,720
He's the world's greatest
authority on rubber trees.

888
01:00:32,795 --> 01:00:35,423
He's been to the Amazon
30 times. He always says,

889
01:00:35,498 --> 01:00:37,489
[Scottish Accent]
"I'm verra, verra fond
of the wee river."

890
01:00:37,567 --> 01:00:40,195
He talks like that
and calls me laddie.
[Chuckles]

891
01:00:40,269 --> 01:00:44,603
Laddie?

892
01:00:44,674 --> 01:00:49,134
Do you have to go?
It's sort of a declaration
of independence to Dad.

893
01:00:49,212 --> 01:00:53,080
He's got a lot of ideas about
handing me a ready-made future.

894
01:00:53,149 --> 01:00:56,209
Oh, I see.

895
01:00:56,285 --> 01:00:59,152
Look at that traffic.
And it's after 12:00.

896
01:00:59,222 --> 01:01:04,922
Yes, it certainly is.
Will you be away long?
About six months.

897
01:01:04,994 --> 01:01:07,554
Where will you stay?
On our boat.

898
01:01:07,630 --> 01:01:11,999
It's a big sailboat
with an auxiliary,
a diesel engine.

899
01:01:12,068 --> 01:01:14,332
Sailboats are beautiful.

900
01:01:14,404 --> 01:01:16,531
Yes, they are beautiful.

901
01:01:26,649 --> 01:01:28,913
What's a diesel engine?

902
01:01:28,985 --> 01:01:32,250
Well, it's on the same principal
as a regular gasoline engine...

903
01:01:32,321 --> 01:01:35,552
only instead
of using crude oil...

904
01:01:35,625 --> 01:01:38,253
Did you say it was 12:00?

905
01:01:38,327 --> 01:01:40,454
It's after 12:00.
See the clock down there?

906
01:01:40,530 --> 01:01:42,862
Oh, l...
Well, good-bye.

907
01:01:42,932 --> 01:01:45,093
[Indistinct Chatter]

908
01:01:45,168 --> 01:01:47,261
Wait a minute!

909
01:01:47,336 --> 01:01:51,466
[Orchestra]

910
01:02:10,059 --> 01:02:12,027
[Ted]
You're not gonna run away,
are you?

911
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:20,093
[Barbara]
Hello, Ted.

912
01:02:20,169 --> 01:02:22,103
Hello, Mrs. Clinton.
Walter.

913
01:02:22,171 --> 01:02:24,139
We've had
an appalling experience.
We're jailbirds.

914
01:02:24,207 --> 01:02:26,869
What are you doing
with that slipper?
Looking for it's owner.

915
01:02:26,943 --> 01:02:29,104
I'll be right back.
Who'd he say
he was looking for?

916
01:02:29,178 --> 01:02:31,669
- I don't know.
- [Grace] He's probably playing some game.

917
01:02:31,748 --> 01:02:34,012
[Walter]
He seemed delighted we were
here.
[Man] Hello, Grace.

918
01:02:34,083 --> 01:02:36,449
[Woman]
We thought you'd never get here.
We were delayed.

919
01:02:36,519 --> 01:02:38,453
By the law.
Wasn't it horrible, dear?

920
01:02:38,521 --> 01:02:40,546
It wasn't fun.
I rather enjoyed it.

921
01:02:40,623 --> 01:02:44,423
What happened?
Oh, Ted. Your father
knows the mayor, doesn't he?

922
01:02:44,494 --> 01:02:46,621
Yes...
Mother wants to reform
the whole city government.

923
01:02:46,696 --> 01:02:48,630
Good.
Excuse me a minute.

924
01:02:48,698 --> 01:02:51,963
You didn't see a girl
go any place without a slipper,
did you?
No.

925
01:02:52,034 --> 01:02:54,867
Well...
Be back in a minute.

926
01:02:54,937 --> 01:02:57,531
I never heard of such
inefficiency.
Does anybody know who...

927
01:02:57,607 --> 01:02:59,973
Ted's looking for?
[Woman] Probably
the girl who was singing.

928
01:03:00,042 --> 01:03:02,340
[Barbara]
He's certainly
in a dither about her.

929
01:03:02,411 --> 01:03:04,845
[Walter]
Let's all go up
and help him find her.

930
01:03:25,034 --> 01:03:27,298
Did you see that girl
with the white wrap?
She looked just like Connie.

931
01:03:27,370 --> 01:03:29,338
It can't be.
Connie isn't here.

932
01:03:29,405 --> 01:03:31,566
Did that wrap she
was wearing have a hood?
I don't know.

933
01:03:31,641 --> 01:03:33,575
Have you seen
Ted running around
with that slipper?

934
01:03:33,643 --> 01:03:35,543
I thought it was yours
'til I saw how small it was.

935
01:03:35,611 --> 01:03:38,444
It belonged to some new girl,
somebody no one ever saw before.

936
01:03:38,514 --> 01:03:40,948
Shejust ran away
with the party. Nobody's
seen Ted since she sang.

937
01:03:41,017 --> 01:03:45,351
And when she danced,
shejust closed her eyes
and lost herself in a dream.

938
01:03:45,421 --> 01:03:48,515
Did that girl wear
a silver-lace dress?
Uh-huh. Very sweet.

939
01:03:48,591 --> 01:03:51,685
Not severe like your black.
Just girlish. Do you know her?

940
01:03:51,761 --> 01:03:54,355
Tell you later.
Get my wrap, please.
Yes, miss.

941
01:03:57,033 --> 01:03:58,660
We've been waiting for you,
miss.
Oh, George!

942
01:03:58,734 --> 01:04:00,668
Tell us all about it.
I don't know where
to begin.

943
01:04:00,736 --> 01:04:02,670
Any trouble getting in?
No.

944
01:04:02,738 --> 01:04:05,639
- You didn't run into
Mrs. Clinton and the brats?
- No, but I saw them.

945
01:04:05,708 --> 01:04:07,642
[Martha]
Did they see you?
[Agnes] What time?

946
01:04:07,710 --> 01:04:09,701
No, I hid behind a post.
They got in about midnight.
How did you know...

947
01:04:09,779 --> 01:04:12,543
A little bird told us.
[Agnes]
A little bird named Mike.

948
01:04:12,615 --> 01:04:14,310
Did you dance?
Yes, and I sang.

949
01:04:14,383 --> 01:04:18,410
I'll bet they cheered.
And Mr. Drake...

950
01:04:18,487 --> 01:04:21,650
Oh, so that's the "he."
[Whistles]

951
01:04:21,724 --> 01:04:23,521
[Connie] Agnes, it was...
What I wouldn't have given
to see you.

952
01:04:23,593 --> 01:04:26,323
He was so nice, Agnes.
Oh, don't ask me.
[George] What did you sing?

953
01:04:26,395 --> 01:04:30,354
A Strauss waltz. You know.
[Humming]

954
01:04:30,433 --> 01:04:32,799
We'd best go in the kitchen,
miss.
I've got some hot chocolate...

955
01:04:32,869 --> 01:04:35,929
and a piece of cake for you.
And you can start
at the very beginning.

956
01:04:36,005 --> 01:04:37,939
You're lame!
I lost a slipper.

957
01:04:38,007 --> 01:04:40,271
How'd you do that?
It was awful.
I had to start running...

958
01:04:40,343 --> 01:04:44,575
No more here. The old man's
working in his study
and we'll get into a...

959
01:04:46,649 --> 01:04:49,117
I'm working;
you're making noise.

960
01:04:49,185 --> 01:04:51,585
So we'll have to stop the work
or stop the noise.

961
01:04:51,654 --> 01:04:55,590
I'm very sorry.
It's my fault, UncleJim.

962
01:04:55,658 --> 01:04:58,821
Maybe it is.
We won't have any more of it.

963
01:05:05,534 --> 01:05:09,732
UncleJim. George told me
to be quiet or go to another
room so I wouldn't disturb you...

964
01:05:09,805 --> 01:05:11,602
Have a nice time
at the party?

965
01:05:11,674 --> 01:05:16,373
What? Oh, yes, wonderful.
Uh-huh.
Danced, huh?

966
01:05:16,445 --> 01:05:19,414
Met some nice people?
Oh, yes, UncleJim.
Very nice.

967
01:05:19,482 --> 01:05:22,007
What'd your cousin say
when she saw you?

968
01:05:22,084 --> 01:05:25,815
Oh, I didn't speak to Barbara,
Aunt Grace or Walter, either.

969
01:05:25,888 --> 01:05:30,086
Smart girl. Run up
to bed now. Good night.

970
01:05:30,159 --> 01:05:32,024
Good night.

971
01:05:32,094 --> 01:05:36,394
The family must have stopped
someplace on the way...
Yeah, stopped in jail.

972
01:05:36,465 --> 01:05:39,662
Kept 'em there
'til midnight. Should have
kept 'em there longer.

973
01:05:39,735 --> 01:05:43,466
Jail? What happened?
Don't know.

974
01:05:43,539 --> 01:05:46,440
They called me to get
my lawyer. Couldn't get him.

975
01:05:46,509 --> 01:05:48,943
Couldn't remember
his telephone number.

976
01:05:49,011 --> 01:05:53,948
Couldn't even remember his name.
Couldn't remember anything.

977
01:05:55,184 --> 01:05:59,382
I don't understand.
Had a good time,
you said.

978
01:05:59,455 --> 01:06:03,824
You knew about
UncleJason?

979
01:06:03,893 --> 01:06:08,227
I know a lot of things.
I know every cloud
has a silver lining.

980
01:06:08,297 --> 01:06:10,891
They went to jail;
you went to the ball.

981
01:06:10,967 --> 01:06:13,731
UncleJim, you...
Oh!

982
01:06:13,803 --> 01:06:16,966
Car coming up the driveway.
This is all a secret.

983
01:06:17,039 --> 01:06:21,339
I'll never tell a soul.
Make my life miserable
if you do. Yours too.

984
01:06:21,410 --> 01:06:23,640
It's Barbara.
You'd better scat.

985
01:06:23,713 --> 01:06:25,647
Good night.

986
01:06:30,586 --> 01:06:32,417
Hurry up!

987
01:06:32,488 --> 01:06:34,547
The duchess is coming!

988
01:06:34,623 --> 01:06:36,648
[Car Door Slams]

989
01:06:55,077 --> 01:06:59,411
Are you asleep?
Uh-huh. Ooh, that light
hurts my eyes.

990
01:06:59,482 --> 01:07:04,476
- I just wanted to see
that you were in.
- I'm in. Good night.

991
01:07:04,553 --> 01:07:07,283
Have you been in all night?
What time is it?

992
01:07:07,356 --> 01:07:10,223
- You were home all night?
- UncleJason didn't arrive.

993
01:07:10,292 --> 01:07:14,285
Sorry if I interrupted
your beauty sleep.
That's all right.

994
01:07:33,416 --> 01:07:36,351
So you were at the party.
Yes.

995
01:07:36,419 --> 01:07:39,217
And you sang.
Um-hmm.
I sang.

996
01:07:39,288 --> 01:07:43,486
Didn't I tell you
to stay here?
I didn't want to.

997
01:07:43,559 --> 01:07:46,119
Oh, you didn't want to.

998
01:07:46,195 --> 01:07:49,164
Nope. I knew UncleJason
wasn't coming and I had
a chance to go, so I went.

999
01:07:49,231 --> 01:07:53,725
- You mean you sneaked in.
- There's nothing you can do that
could spoil this night for me.

1000
01:07:53,803 --> 01:07:57,933
Would it spoil things if I asked
how you turned your graduation
dress into a Paris creation?

1001
01:07:58,007 --> 01:08:02,501
OIlie made it out of some
silver lace I had. Not that
it's any of your business.

1002
01:08:02,578 --> 01:08:06,105
And that wrap. She made that
out of a pair of pet ermine
she's been keeping?

1003
01:08:06,182 --> 01:08:09,845
A friend of mine said I could...
I'm not going to quarrel
with you, Barbara.

1004
01:08:09,919 --> 01:08:12,353
I'm so sorry I wasn't there.
You must have been wonderful.

1005
01:08:12,421 --> 01:08:14,787
Thank you. Now, if you're
through being sarcastic...

1006
01:08:14,857 --> 01:08:17,325
Even Ted said he never
had so much fun.

1007
01:08:17,393 --> 01:08:20,521
He thought you were
a night club singer pretending
to be somebody important,

1008
01:08:20,596 --> 01:08:22,359
so he decided
to play up to it.

1009
01:08:22,431 --> 01:08:26,561
It's so funny. And his
imitation of you dancing with
your eyes shut is wonderful.

1010
01:08:26,635 --> 01:08:30,594
People just roll on the floor
when he does it. He does it
over and over again.

1011
01:08:30,673 --> 01:08:32,402
And leaving your slipper.
That was so touching.

1012
01:08:32,475 --> 01:08:34,170
Ted's going to use it
to try and find you.

1013
01:08:34,243 --> 01:08:36,336
He wants to hire you
to play the same joke
on a friend of his in Boston.

1014
01:08:36,412 --> 01:08:39,848
You get out of here.
This is my room and l...

1015
01:08:39,915 --> 01:08:43,817
Oh, you want to be alone.
You have so much to think about,
so much to dream over.

1016
01:08:43,886 --> 01:08:45,820
Get out!
All right.

1017
01:08:45,888 --> 01:08:49,346
I'll go down to the kitchen
and tell your chums
what a success you were.

1018
01:08:51,427 --> 01:08:53,418
[Sobbing]

1019
01:08:59,301 --> 01:09:01,531
Good morning, sir.
Good morning.

1020
01:09:01,604 --> 01:09:03,538
Your orange juice, sir.
Um-hmm.

1021
01:09:03,606 --> 01:09:05,904
Your coffee black
as usual?
Um-hmm.

1022
01:09:05,975 --> 01:09:08,705
Anything else, sir?
Not a thing.

1023
01:09:12,148 --> 01:09:14,207
Then this is good-bye,
sir.

1024
01:09:15,484 --> 01:09:17,884
Going someplace?

1025
01:09:17,953 --> 01:09:21,480
I'm leaving, sir.
Miss Barbara sacked
the whole staff last night...

1026
01:09:21,557 --> 01:09:23,684
when she found out we'd helped
Miss Connie get to the party.

1027
01:09:23,759 --> 01:09:25,693
What?
Oh, that's all right, sir.

1028
01:09:25,761 --> 01:09:28,992
Not one of us would have stayed
after Miss Connie left.

1029
01:09:30,599 --> 01:09:33,067
Connie left?

1030
01:09:33,135 --> 01:09:37,902
Bag and baggage, sir.
We wanted her to stay
and have a talk with you, sir,

1031
01:09:37,973 --> 01:09:39,964
but she said she had
made enough trouble.

1032
01:09:40,042 --> 01:09:42,875
And didn't leave a note?
She said she'd
write to you, sir,

1033
01:09:42,945 --> 01:09:45,675
when she was settled
and making her own way.

1034
01:09:45,748 --> 01:09:50,481
I do think she was trying
to make it easier...
for us all.

1035
01:09:50,553 --> 01:09:53,113
I'd like to talk
to the other servants, George.

1036
01:09:53,189 --> 01:09:57,922
They've been
gone hours, sir.
[Mrs. Clinton]Jimmie.!

1037
01:09:57,993 --> 01:10:01,360
Jimmie, you have to
drive me into town.
We have no chauffeur.

1038
01:10:01,430 --> 01:10:06,299
Did you know that Connie had left?
Yes, so has everyone else.
No cook, no butler, no maids.

1039
01:10:06,368 --> 01:10:08,393
And you're not with us
anymore, are you, George?

1040
01:10:08,470 --> 01:10:11,496
- No, madam, I'm not.
- Such a pity.
You're such a good butler too.

1041
01:10:11,574 --> 01:10:17,103
It was nothing personal. Just a bad
constellation for everybody.
It won't happen again.

1042
01:10:17,179 --> 01:10:20,808
Connie's a very young girl
to be out on her own.
It's not right.

1043
01:10:20,883 --> 01:10:24,250
I'm going to look up her
horoscope and find out what evil
influence brought this about.

1044
01:10:24,320 --> 01:10:27,084
I'm also going to see
if it's a good time
to employ new people.

1045
01:10:27,156 --> 01:10:29,124
We have to wait
until the stars are right.

1046
01:10:29,191 --> 01:10:33,093
I'm hungry.
The cook has left,
Mr. Walter.

1047
01:10:33,162 --> 01:10:36,097
Father, can you make coffee?

1048
01:10:38,167 --> 01:10:42,228
Do you know that your cousin
has left this house?

1049
01:10:42,304 --> 01:10:44,795
I only know
I'm hungry.

1050
01:10:51,914 --> 01:10:55,315
Don't you think we better
do something practical
about Connie?

1051
01:10:55,384 --> 01:10:57,944
I'm doing the most
practical thing in the world:

1052
01:10:58,020 --> 01:11:00,989
Checking her
complementary influence
againstJupiter's emphasis.

1053
01:11:01,056 --> 01:11:03,991
Then there's a trend
of depression that's been...
[Continues Indistinct]

1054
01:11:21,076 --> 01:11:23,476
Jim, what are you doing?

1055
01:11:25,114 --> 01:11:29,915
Jim, it's taken me years
to work that all out!

1056
01:11:29,985 --> 01:11:32,647
I never liked
this thing, either!

1057
01:11:34,757 --> 01:11:37,351
Jim, stop it!
Are you losing your mind?

1058
01:11:37,426 --> 01:11:39,553
Now, you listen to me,
Gracie Schultz!

1059
01:11:39,628 --> 01:11:42,392
I've had all the twaddle
I'm gonna have about
the eight and ninth house...

1060
01:11:42,464 --> 01:11:46,764
and the influence of this and
that, and Leo being in Libra
that I'm gonna have!

1061
01:11:46,835 --> 01:11:48,769
I oughta make you
eat these things!

1062
01:11:48,837 --> 01:11:52,466
But if I ever hear
another peep outta you
about the sun, moon or stars,

1063
01:11:52,541 --> 01:11:54,839
I promise you by the big
and little dipper,

1064
01:11:54,910 --> 01:11:58,539
that you won't be only
talkin' about stars,
you'll be seein' 'em!

1065
01:11:58,614 --> 01:12:00,878
[Sobbing]
Let the heavens take care
of themselves!

1066
01:12:00,949 --> 01:12:05,010
And you get down to earth!
Aurgh!

1067
01:12:05,087 --> 01:12:07,920
[Sobbing]
Oh, Jim, you brute!
Don't flatter me!

1068
01:12:07,990 --> 01:12:10,891
- I've only just begun!
- Father, have you gone crazy?

1069
01:12:10,959 --> 01:12:13,757
[Sobbing Continues]
Oh, you're up.
That's fine.

1070
01:12:13,829 --> 01:12:17,060
I was hoping I wouldn't have to
go and pull you out of bed.
Mother!

1071
01:12:17,132 --> 01:12:19,123
Why did you make Connie
leave this house?

1072
01:12:19,201 --> 01:12:21,465
Now, Father.
Don't "Father" me! I know
what you did and for once...

1073
01:12:21,537 --> 01:12:23,630
you're gonna pay
the consequences,
you selfish...

1074
01:12:23,706 --> 01:12:25,901
little dressed up ingrate!
I won't be talked to
like that!

1075
01:12:25,974 --> 01:12:28,704
Then we'll stop talking!
You come in here!
Mother!

1076
01:12:28,777 --> 01:12:31,837
You're a child and I'm gonna
treat you like a child.!

1077
01:12:31,914 --> 01:12:33,905
[Barbara Protesting]

1078
01:12:40,289 --> 01:12:44,055
[Barbara Yelling]
Daddy, don't.!
[Mr. Clinton Spanking Barbara]

1079
01:12:47,529 --> 01:12:49,656
[Yelling Continues]

1080
01:12:49,732 --> 01:12:52,428
I'll pay you for this.
Oh, no, sir,
this one's on me.

1081
01:12:52,501 --> 01:12:55,902
There's one more thing
I want you to...

1082
01:13:16,225 --> 01:13:19,661
Don't you ever do anything
but sit sprawled out
in that chair?

1083
01:13:19,728 --> 01:13:22,060
But, Father, I have
a theory, you know.
Really?

1084
01:13:22,131 --> 01:13:26,534
A theory of relaxation.
I worked it all out myself.
In that chair?

1085
01:13:26,602 --> 01:13:28,570
Um-hmm.
It's taken years.

1086
01:13:28,637 --> 01:13:32,073
I believe that one
through relaxation,
prolonged and constant,

1087
01:13:32,141 --> 01:13:35,770
can store up sufficient energy
to surmount any emergency
that arises...

1088
01:13:35,844 --> 01:13:39,280
where vitality is called for
and force is needed.

1089
01:13:39,348 --> 01:13:41,816
Simple, isn't it?
Almost too simple.

1090
01:13:41,884 --> 01:13:44,148
You see, I don't spend energy,
I hoard it.

1091
01:13:44,219 --> 01:13:47,154
Sort of sit on it?
Exactly.

1092
01:13:47,222 --> 01:13:50,191
I've already proved all forms
of exercise are wrong.

1093
01:13:50,259 --> 01:13:52,659
Say a man gets up
and does his daily dozen.

1094
01:13:52,728 --> 01:13:55,390
The first time
he stretches,

1095
01:13:55,464 --> 01:13:57,864
bends over,
touches the floor,

1096
01:13:57,933 --> 01:14:00,731
he's spent 14 pounds
of energy.

1097
01:14:00,803 --> 01:14:03,795
To get back to
his normal position, how much
do you think he spends?

1098
01:14:03,872 --> 01:14:08,502
Uh, from the position
you were in just now?

1099
01:14:08,577 --> 01:14:11,239
Um-hmm. Identical with it.
Just about...

1100
01:14:11,313 --> 01:14:14,771
Practically none, because
I'd help him like that!

1101
01:14:17,753 --> 01:14:20,347
Very well bowled, sir.

1102
01:14:21,490 --> 01:14:26,723
There's only one more thing
we gotta do! Find Connie
and bring her back here!

1103
01:14:26,795 --> 01:14:29,263
Everybody understand that?

1104
01:14:37,139 --> 01:14:40,404
This is your station, miss.
Thank you.

1105
01:14:43,479 --> 01:14:48,109
[Brakes Squealing]

1106
01:14:48,183 --> 01:14:50,242
[Cane Raps On Window]

1107
01:14:54,656 --> 01:14:58,023
Oh, Miss Wiggins.
Did you get my telegram?

1108
01:14:58,093 --> 01:15:01,620
No, I meet all the trains.
That's all I have to do.

1109
01:15:01,697 --> 01:15:05,064
Did I get your telegram?
Get those bags over here.

1110
01:15:08,871 --> 01:15:10,998
It's so quiet
and restful here.

1111
01:15:11,073 --> 01:15:14,509
Going through that stage, eh?
Cities are
such noisy places.

1112
01:15:14,576 --> 01:15:17,841
They're not dull
and full of squealing girls.

1113
01:15:17,913 --> 01:15:20,381
Are you surprised
that I'm back?
Nope.

1114
01:15:20,449 --> 01:15:26,285
You must be.
All right then, I will be.
I'm surprised. Feel better?

1115
01:15:26,355 --> 01:15:30,257
I wanna teach music.
Most of them
want to be missionaries.

1116
01:15:30,325 --> 01:15:33,556
Who?
Never mind. Go on.
You want to teach.

1117
01:15:33,629 --> 01:15:37,326
Yes, but I'll have to
have more training.
I hope so.

1118
01:15:37,399 --> 01:15:40,926
I'd like to get
a scholarship at the Teacher's
Conservatory of Music.

1119
01:15:41,003 --> 01:15:45,099
Um-hmm.
I suppose it's only fair
that I tell you...

1120
01:15:45,173 --> 01:15:47,573
why I've made this decision,
Miss Wiggins.

1121
01:15:47,643 --> 01:15:52,478
Practice that little speech
on the way up?
Why... I guess I did.

1122
01:15:52,548 --> 01:15:54,743
What's that?
I guess I did.

1123
01:15:54,816 --> 01:15:57,614
Never mind the rest.
I know the important part.

1124
01:15:57,686 --> 01:16:00,450
Your heart's broken,
your faith's gone,
you want to be independent...

1125
01:16:00,522 --> 01:16:04,583
Who told you?
About 40 old maids I know.
It happened to them too.

1126
01:16:04,660 --> 01:16:08,562
Make it 41.
I'd forgotten myself.

1127
01:16:08,630 --> 01:16:12,225
This is so...
Oh, you don't want
to hear about it.

1128
01:16:12,301 --> 01:16:14,360
Oh, go on,
get it off your chest.

1129
01:16:14,436 --> 01:16:17,837
Might make you feel better,
and it won't make me
feel any worse.

1130
01:16:19,241 --> 01:16:21,004
First, you'll be
a junior instructor.

1131
01:16:21,076 --> 01:16:25,376
You'll get paid half as much
as you need to live on,
if you call it living.

1132
01:16:25,447 --> 01:16:29,383
You'll wear last year's hats,
two-year-old dresses
and patched up shoes.

1133
01:16:29,451 --> 01:16:31,919
But it won't make much
difference how you look
'cause there won't be...

1134
01:16:31,987 --> 01:16:34,478
anybody lookin' at you,
except a lot
of so-called students.

1135
01:16:34,556 --> 01:16:37,855
I'll have my work.
You'll have that.

1136
01:16:37,926 --> 01:16:40,690
Later on by scrimping
you'll have money to travel on...

1137
01:16:40,762 --> 01:16:43,595
third class and alone,
or with another teacher.

1138
01:16:43,665 --> 01:16:48,500
I like to be alone.
You don't even know
what the word means, child!

1139
01:16:48,570 --> 01:16:52,028
My pupils will love me, I hope,
as much as they love you.

1140
01:16:52,107 --> 01:16:55,076
I'm a character, a crotchety,
loveable old character.

1141
01:16:55,143 --> 01:16:59,011
I hate being a character.
Do you like cats?

1142
01:16:59,081 --> 01:17:03,245
- No, not much.
- Huh. You'll get
to love them.

1143
01:17:03,318 --> 01:17:05,912
They've got sense.
They're like men:

1144
01:17:05,988 --> 01:17:09,651
Feed them, pet them and
admire them and they'll purr.

1145
01:17:09,725 --> 01:17:12,250
Every woman
wants to make somebody purr.

1146
01:17:12,327 --> 01:17:16,320
You want to lock yourself up
in a world of women, a little
world, a sheltered world.

1147
01:17:16,398 --> 01:17:18,559
A useless, polite
frightened world.

1148
01:17:18,634 --> 01:17:21,865
Miss Wiggins, I'm not a child.
I know what I want to do.

1149
01:17:21,937 --> 01:17:26,431
Work and support myself
and not depend on other people
for happiness or anything else.

1150
01:17:29,277 --> 01:17:34,146
All right.
Where's your diploma?

1151
01:17:34,216 --> 01:17:38,414
I'll have to sent it along
with the application
for the scholarship.

1152
01:17:38,487 --> 01:17:40,614
It's right here.

1153
01:17:42,524 --> 01:17:46,085
There's a teacher's powwow
here on the sixth.

1154
01:17:46,161 --> 01:17:48,789
They'll be here
from all over the state.

1155
01:17:48,864 --> 01:17:52,061
We'll have to line up
some votes for you
while they're on the ground.

1156
01:17:52,134 --> 01:17:56,195
Here's a list of credits.
Hmm, pretty slipper.

1157
01:17:56,271 --> 01:18:00,071
The other one, I suppose,
is the one Mr. Blake had.
Mr. Drake.

1158
01:18:00,142 --> 01:18:02,940
What you keeping it for?
I just happened to pack it.

1159
01:18:03,011 --> 01:18:08,039
To have something to cry into
30 years from now?
Get rid of it.

1160
01:18:11,119 --> 01:18:13,314
You'll sing at that meeting,

1161
01:18:13,388 --> 01:18:15,948
show them a sample
of what you know
about music,

1162
01:18:16,024 --> 01:18:18,356
have them make up
their minds right away.

1163
01:18:18,427 --> 01:18:21,055
Thank you.
That'll be marvelous.

1164
01:18:21,129 --> 01:18:24,257
It'll be terrible, but I'll do it.
You'll get a new dress for it.

1165
01:18:24,332 --> 01:18:27,665
I'll have the girls go to
the auditorium so you'll
have an audience...

1166
01:18:27,736 --> 01:18:29,727
and you'll sing something
that will be effective.

1167
01:18:29,805 --> 01:18:32,137
The Spring Song.
No, not the Spring Song.

1168
01:18:32,207 --> 01:18:34,971
One fine day.
"Butterfly" by Puccini.

1169
01:18:35,043 --> 01:18:37,807
Know it?
Yes.

1170
01:18:37,879 --> 01:18:41,576
We have to work on it.
That'll make 'em all cry.

1171
01:18:41,650 --> 01:18:43,914
All the old maids
will sniffle.

1172
01:18:43,985 --> 01:18:46,886
You know, "One fine day
he'll come back to me."

1173
01:18:46,955 --> 01:18:49,890
Oh, but l...
I'd rather... l...

1174
01:18:49,958 --> 01:18:53,325
Rather what?
Couldn't I sing
something else?

1175
01:18:53,395 --> 01:18:57,354
Why?
I don't think it's a good idea
to make them sad.

1176
01:18:57,432 --> 01:18:59,525
Make you sad
to sing it?

1177
01:18:59,601 --> 01:19:03,537
No, no, not me.
You just said it'd
make them cry.

1178
01:19:03,605 --> 01:19:07,097
Old maids are
only happy when they cry.
You'll find that out.

1179
01:19:07,175 --> 01:19:09,166
[Knock At Door]

1180
01:19:09,244 --> 01:19:12,008
Miss Wiggins, we just heard
that Connie was... Oh!

1181
01:19:12,080 --> 01:19:15,049
Hello, Connie!
When did you get back?

1182
01:19:15,117 --> 01:19:17,881
[Chattering]
Go along, all of you,
and stop chattering.

1183
01:19:17,953 --> 01:19:21,821
[Chattering Continues]

1184
01:19:26,128 --> 01:19:28,926
Why didn't you go
with Connie?
I don't know her.

1185
01:19:28,997 --> 01:19:32,228
I came in to see
if you would mark the cuts
in this orchestration for me.

1186
01:19:32,300 --> 01:19:34,359
Irene told me to do it...
I'll fix it.

1187
01:19:34,436 --> 01:19:37,462
You will?
Thanks a lot, Miss Wiggins!
Good-bye!

1188
01:19:41,476 --> 01:19:44,138
I said I'll fix it,
didn't I?

1189
01:19:45,680 --> 01:19:47,477
[Skipped item nr. 1189]

1190
01:19:47,549 --> 01:19:51,713
Weeping and why

1191
01:19:51,787 --> 01:19:55,086
And why

1192
01:19:55,157 --> 01:20:02,256
On his face
you are looking

1193
01:20:02,330 --> 01:20:07,290
Hear me

1194
01:20:08,603 --> 01:20:15,532
One fine day
we'll notice

1195
01:20:15,610 --> 01:20:22,015
A thread of smoke arising

1196
01:20:22,083 --> 01:20:25,075
On the sea

1197
01:20:25,153 --> 01:20:30,147
In the far horizon

1198
01:20:30,225 --> 01:20:32,693
And then

1199
01:20:32,761 --> 01:20:38,461
The ship appearing

1200
01:20:38,533 --> 01:20:44,199
Then the trim white vessel

1201
01:20:44,272 --> 01:20:47,639
Glides

1202
01:20:47,709 --> 01:20:52,544
Into the harbor

1203
01:20:52,614 --> 01:20:59,110
Thunders forth her cannon

1204
01:20:59,187 --> 01:21:03,214
See you

1205
01:21:03,291 --> 01:21:08,752
Now he is coming

1206
01:21:08,830 --> 01:21:15,429
I do not go to meet him

1207
01:21:15,503 --> 01:21:17,801
Not I

1208
01:21:17,873 --> 01:21:24,073
I stay upon the brow
of the hillock

1209
01:21:24,145 --> 01:21:26,340
And wait there

1210
01:21:26,414 --> 01:21:32,353
And wait
for a long time

1211
01:21:32,420 --> 01:21:36,914
But never weary

1212
01:21:36,992 --> 01:21:42,726
Of the long waiting

1213
01:21:42,797 --> 01:21:46,028
From out the crowded city

1214
01:21:46,101 --> 01:21:49,593
[Whispers]
Miss Wiggins.
There is coming

1215
01:21:49,671 --> 01:21:58,136
A little, little speck
in the distance

1216
01:21:58,213 --> 01:22:05,085
Climbing the hillock

1217
01:22:06,388 --> 01:22:09,880
Can you guess
who it is

1218
01:22:09,958 --> 01:22:12,620
And when he's reached
the summit

1219
01:22:12,694 --> 01:22:16,960
Can you guess
what he'll say

1220
01:22:17,032 --> 01:22:19,796
He will call

1221
01:22:19,868 --> 01:22:25,033
Butterfly from the distance

1222
01:22:25,106 --> 01:22:30,806
I, without answering, hold
myself quietly concealed

1223
01:22:30,879 --> 01:22:34,076
A bit to tease him

1224
01:22:34,149 --> 01:22:37,118
And a bit

1225
01:22:37,185 --> 01:22:41,554
So as not to die

1226
01:22:41,623 --> 01:22:45,889
At our first meeting

1227
01:22:45,961 --> 01:22:50,557
And then a little troubled
he will call

1228
01:22:50,632 --> 01:22:54,591
He will call

1229
01:22:54,669 --> 01:22:58,400
Dear baby wife of mine

1230
01:22:58,473 --> 01:23:03,240
Dear little orange blossom

1231
01:23:03,311 --> 01:23:06,644
The names
he used to call me

1232
01:23:06,715 --> 01:23:11,880
When he came here

1233
01:23:11,953 --> 01:23:17,118
This will all come to pass
as I tell you

1234
01:23:17,192 --> 01:23:22,152
Banish your idle fears

1235
01:23:22,230 --> 01:23:27,031
For he shall return

1236
01:23:27,102 --> 01:23:33,598
He shall

